SIMPLE: strain
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Strain
<hw>Strain</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Strene</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Race; stock; generation;
descent; family.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He is of a noble <qex>strain</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With animals and plants a cross between different varieties, or
between individuals of the same variety but of another
<qex>strain</qex>, gives vigor and fertility to the offspring.</q>
<rj><qau>Darwin.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hereditary character, quality, or
disposition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Intemperance and lust breed diseases, which, propogated, spoil the
<qex>strain</qex> of nation.</q> <rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Rank; a sort.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The common
<xex>strain</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Hort.)</fld> <def>A cultural subvariety that is
only slightly differentiated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Strain</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Strain
<hw>Strain</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Strained</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Straining</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF. <ets>estraindre</ets>,
<ets>estreindre</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧treindre</ets>, L.
<ets>stringere</ets> to draw or bind tight; probably akin to Gr. <?/ a
halter, <?/ that which is squeezwd out, a drop, or perhaps to E.
<ets>strike</ets>. Cf. <er>Strangle</er>, <er>Strike</er>,
<er>Constrain</er>, <er>District</er>, <er>Strait</er>, <pos>a.</pos>
<er>Stress</er>, <er>Strict</er>, <er>Stringent</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To draw with force; to extend with great effort; to stretch;
<as>as, to <ex>strain</ex> a rope; to <ex>strain</ex> the shrouds of a
ship; to <ex>strain</ex> the cords of a musical instrument</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧To <xex>strain</xex> his fetters with a stricter care.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>To act upon, in any way, so as to
cause change of form or volume, as forces on a beam to bend
it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To exert to the utmost; to ply vigorously.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He sweats,⟦br⟧
<qex>Strains</qex> his young nerves.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>strain</qex> their warbling throats⟦br⟧
To welcome in the spring.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To stretch beyond its proper limit; to do violence
to, in the matter of intent or meaning; <as>as, to <ex>strain</ex> the
law in order to convict an accused person</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There can be no other meaning in this expression, however some may
pretend to <qex>strain</qex> it.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To injure by drawing, stretching, or the exertion of
force; <as>as, the gale <ex>strained</ex> the timbers of the
ship</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To injure in the muscles or joints by causing to
make too strong an effort; to harm by overexertion; to sprain; <as>as,
to <ex>strain</ex> a horse by overloading; to <ex>strain</ex> the wrist;
to <ex>strain</ex> a muscle</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Prudes decayed about may track,⟦br⟧
<qex>Strain</qex> their necks with looking back.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To squeeze; to press closely.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Evander with a close embrace⟦br⟧
<qex>Strained</qex> his departing friend.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To make uneasy or unnatural; to produce with
apparent effort; to force; to constrain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He talks and plays with Fatima, but his mirth⟦br⟧
Is forced and <qex>strained</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The quality of mercy is not <qex>strained</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To urge with importunity; to press; <as>as, to
<ex>strain</ex> a petition or invitation</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Note, if your lady <qex>strain</qex> his entertainment.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>To press, or cause to pass, through a strainer, as
through a screen, a cloth, or some porous substance; to purify, or
separate from extraneous or solid matter, by filtration; to filter;
<as>as, to <ex>strain</ex> milk through cloth</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To strain a point</b></col>, <cd>to make a special
effort; especially, to do a degree of violence to some principle or to
one's own feelings.</cd> -- <col><b>To strain courtesy</b></col>, <cd>to
go beyond what courtesy requires; to insist somewhat too much upon the
precedence of others; -- often used ironically.</cd>
<au>Shak.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1422 --></p>

<p><ent>Strain</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Strain
<hw>Strain</hw> <pr>(str⟦amac⟧n)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To make violent efforts.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Straining</xex> with too
weak a wing.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To build his fortune I will <qex>strain</qex> a little.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To percolate; to be filtered; <as>as, water
<ex>straining</ex> through a sandy soil</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Strain</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Strain
<hw>Strain</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of straining, or
the state of being strained.</def> Specifically: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <def>A violent effort; an excessive and hurtful exertion
or tension, as of the muscles; <as>as, he lifted the weight with a
<ex>strain</ex>; the <ex>strain</ex> upon a ship's rigging in a
gale;</as> also, the hurt or injury resulting; a sprain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whether any poet of our country since Shakespeare has exerted a
greater variety of powers with less <qex>strain</qex> and less
ostentation.</q> <rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Credit is gained by custom, and seldom recovers a
<qex>strain</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Mech. Physics)</fld> <def>A change of form or
dimensions of a solid or liquid mass, produced by a stress.</def>
<rj><au>Rankine.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A portion of music divided off by
a double bar; a complete musical period or sentence; a movement, or any
rounded subdivision of a movement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their heavenly harps a lower <qex>strain</qex> began.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any sustained note or movement; a song; a distinct
portion of an ode or other poem; also, the pervading note, or burden, of
a song, poem, oration, book, etc.; theme; motive; manner; style; also, a
course of action or conduct; <as>as, he spoke in a noble
<ex>strain</ex>; there was a <ex>strain</ex> of woe in his story; a
<ex>strain</ex> of trickery appears in his career</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A
<xex>strain</xex> of gallantry.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir W.
Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such take too high a <qex>strain</qex> at first.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The genius and <qex>strain</qex> of the book of Proverbs.</q>
<rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It [Pilgrim's Progress] seems a novelty, and yet contains⟦br⟧
Nothing but sound and honest gospel <qex>strains</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Bunyan.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Turn; tendency; inborn disposition. Cf. 1st
<er>Strain</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Because heretics have a <qex>strain</qex> of madness, he applied
her with some corporal chastisements.</q>
<rj><qau>Hayward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Strainable</ent>⟦br⟧
